WEBVTT

00:02.393 --> 00:05.353
[soft dramatic music]

00:05.396 --> 00:08.530
♪

00:08.573 --> 00:10.053
- Whoa! Oh!

00:10.097 --> 00:11.359
Sorry.
- I'm sorry, I should--

00:11.402 --> 00:13.013
- Excuse me.
- Dr. Snow?

00:13.056 --> 00:14.797
- Yes. Thank goodness they
finally sent someone

00:14.840 --> 00:16.494
to fix the sink.
It's been leaking for weeks.

00:16.538 --> 00:18.279
- Yeah, I don't know anything
about a sink.

00:18.322 --> 00:20.498
I was hoping that
you could fix that.

00:20.542 --> 00:23.284
- Oh, uh, yes.
Yes, of course.

00:23.327 --> 00:25.112
Have--have a seat on the bed.

00:25.155 --> 00:26.417
- Thank you.

00:26.461 --> 00:28.071
I'm normally really careful,

00:28.115 --> 00:30.943
but Dr. Wells has this thing
about deadlines.

00:30.987 --> 00:32.728
- Ah.

00:32.771 --> 00:35.122
- I guess
I was pushing things a little.

00:35.165 --> 00:36.688
How's it look, Doc?

00:36.732 --> 00:39.778
- Uh, it's not so bad.

00:39.822 --> 00:42.651
Probably just a superficial
second-degree burn.

00:42.694 --> 00:44.653
I think you'll be okay.

00:44.696 --> 00:47.569
I know what you mean
about Dr. Wells, though,

00:47.612 --> 00:50.398
but...he is brilliant.

00:51.355 --> 00:53.096
So how did this happen?

00:53.140 --> 00:54.967
- I was fitting
a high pressure coil

00:55.011 --> 00:56.882
down in the pipeline, and,

00:56.926 --> 00:58.754
well, you'd think that
a structural engineer

00:58.797 --> 01:01.322
would know not to touch one
without protection, but--

01:01.365 --> 01:02.671
[winces]
- [gasps]

01:02.714 --> 01:04.629
Sorry.
- Mm-mm, mm-mm, it's fine.

01:04.673 --> 01:06.762
It's fine, doesn't even hurt.

01:06.805 --> 01:08.155
I'm fine--it's fine.

01:08.198 --> 01:10.287
Mm.

01:10.331 --> 01:11.593
What do you think,
am I gonna live?

01:11.636 --> 01:14.248
- I think so.

01:14.291 --> 01:18.339
So, um, what's it like
in the pipeline?

01:18.382 --> 01:21.559
I mean, working inside it.

01:21.603 --> 01:23.126
On it?

01:23.170 --> 01:25.041
Sorry, it's just--

01:25.085 --> 01:26.695
it must be incredible
to wake up every morning

01:26.738 --> 01:28.479
knowing that
you're building something

01:28.523 --> 01:30.438
that's gonna change the course
of scientific discovery

01:30.481 --> 01:32.266
for generations.

01:32.309 --> 01:34.137
- Yeah, I mean,

01:34.181 --> 01:35.878
I guess I never really
thought of it that way.

01:35.921 --> 01:38.098
I just--I just build things.

01:38.141 --> 01:40.448
I mean, ridiculously
complicated things, mind you,

01:40.491 --> 01:42.276
but at the end of the day,

01:42.319 --> 01:45.017
it's kind of like
I'm a big kid.

01:45.061 --> 01:50.501
Just instead of Legos,
I'm using concrete and steel.

01:50.545 --> 01:52.851
- I used to love those things
when I was a little girl.

01:52.895 --> 01:54.462
- Yeah, me too.

01:54.505 --> 01:57.682
I mean not when
I was a little--a little girl.

01:57.726 --> 02:01.121
You're right.
What we're doing down there,

02:01.164 --> 02:03.732
being a part of it,
it's really incredible.

02:03.775 --> 02:06.300
I guess that makes us
all kinda special.

02:08.998 --> 02:11.000
- Well,
I think you're good to go.

02:12.219 --> 02:14.699
- Good as new.
Thank you.

02:14.743 --> 02:17.137
Dr. Snow.
- It's Caitlin.

02:18.921 --> 02:20.183
- Caitlin.

02:20.227 --> 02:21.619
Nice to meet you.
I'm Ronnie.

02:21.663 --> 02:23.491
- Nice to meet you, Ronnie.

02:27.059 --> 02:29.149
Come back anytime.

02:29.192 --> 02:30.541
- It's nice to know that

02:30.585 --> 02:32.587
you'll always be there
to fix me up.

02:33.588 --> 02:35.155
[distorted echoing]
It's nice to know that

02:35.198 --> 02:36.591
you'll always be there
to fix me up.

02:36.634 --> 02:38.114
[ominous music]

02:38.158 --> 02:40.638
- Ronnie?
How is this possible?

02:40.682 --> 02:44.164
- [echoing] Join in,
help us, come together.

02:44.207 --> 02:46.470
- Together?
I don't understand.

02:46.514 --> 02:48.951
- Not whole without you.

02:48.994 --> 02:50.648
You save us.

02:50.692 --> 02:51.954
- How?

02:51.997 --> 02:55.784
- Memories...
in the snow.

02:55.827 --> 02:57.525
- Ronnie, wait, please.

02:57.568 --> 02:59.396
Tell me how to save you!

03:02.443 --> 03:05.402
[epic music]

03:05.446 --> 03:12.496
♪

03:23.638 --> 03:25.292
- Oh, my God.

03:25.335 --> 03:28.208
What did I do?
- What happened to my mom?

03:28.251 --> 03:30.427
- Iris--
- Hey, where's my mom?

03:30.471 --> 03:31.689
- I don't know.

03:31.733 --> 03:34.126
- Just tell me what happened!

03:34.170 --> 03:36.128
- [groans]

03:36.172 --> 03:37.652
- Okay, you need to back up
right now.

03:37.695 --> 03:39.262
- What is wrong with her?

03:39.306 --> 03:41.395
- She has a--
it's a condition, okay?

03:41.438 --> 03:42.961
It's really hard to explain.

03:43.005 --> 03:44.267
But basically,
when it flares up,

03:44.311 --> 03:45.660
like it is right now,

03:45.703 --> 03:47.314
she loses time.
It's not her fault.

03:47.357 --> 03:48.315
She can't control
what happens next.

03:48.358 --> 03:49.359
- You're lying to me.

03:49.403 --> 03:50.447
She attacked my mom.

03:50.491 --> 03:53.233
- Tinya, I'm so sorry.

03:53.276 --> 03:54.886
- I'm calling Barry.

03:57.280 --> 03:58.803
- What the hell?

03:58.847 --> 04:01.066
- [screams]

04:01.110 --> 04:02.807
[gasping]

04:02.851 --> 04:04.983
- You need to get out of here.

04:05.027 --> 04:06.507
Now!

04:08.378 --> 04:10.424
It's okay.
It's gonna be okay.

04:14.689 --> 04:18.345
- Colin Smith, Megan Landa,
Veronica Binning.

04:18.388 --> 04:20.303
These are potential victims

04:20.347 --> 04:22.653
that Cecile and I
got from Kramer's files.

04:22.697 --> 04:26.309
They all were killed in a fire
of undetermined origin

04:26.353 --> 04:28.050
in the last six months.

04:28.093 --> 04:29.399
- That's way before the deaths

04:29.443 --> 04:30.922
of Stan Mullen
and our other vics.

04:30.966 --> 04:33.273
- We know,
which is why I reached out

04:33.316 --> 04:35.187
to the families
of all of our new victims

04:35.231 --> 04:37.842
to find out if any of them
were dealing with grief.

04:37.886 --> 04:41.455
Now, Megan and Colin
both recently lost a parent,

04:41.498 --> 04:44.893
and Veronica has a sister
who died when they were kids.

04:44.936 --> 04:46.286
- Looks like our
not-so-friendly fire

04:46.329 --> 04:47.765
has been snacking on
people's grief

04:47.809 --> 04:49.332
a lot longer than we thought.

04:49.376 --> 04:50.986
- It's been ahead of us
all along.

04:51.029 --> 04:52.379
- Not anymore.

04:52.422 --> 04:54.598
Now we have a way
to stop it from killing.

04:54.642 --> 04:56.774
- Yeah, I finished encoding
the Cold Fusion Sphere

04:56.818 --> 05:00.474
with Frost and Dr. Tannhauser's
cryo-kinetic RNA signatures.

05:00.517 --> 05:02.258
Next time
there's a barometric anomaly,

05:02.302 --> 05:03.825
we can bring it out
into the field

05:03.868 --> 05:06.306
and, you know, use it
to capture this thing.

05:06.349 --> 05:08.699
- I just wish we knew
where it was gonna pop up next.

05:08.743 --> 05:10.658
- There's gotta be something
we're still missing

05:10.701 --> 05:12.616
that links all the victims.

05:12.660 --> 05:14.226
We find that connection...

05:14.270 --> 05:16.620
- We can figure out
what this fire wants.

05:16.664 --> 05:19.231
- It wants me.

05:19.275 --> 05:21.669
And I know that
because I just saw it.

05:21.712 --> 05:24.889
- But why?
What does it want with you?

05:27.022 --> 05:29.198
- Parker?

05:29.241 --> 05:30.547
- Wait, you know her?

05:30.591 --> 05:32.636
- Yeah,
she's my yoga instructor.

05:32.680 --> 05:34.464
- You recognize anyone else?

05:34.508 --> 05:37.815
- Um, these two.

05:37.859 --> 05:39.382
They were at O'Shaughnessy's

05:39.426 --> 05:41.384
the night Frost and I
went on our double date.

05:41.428 --> 05:43.865
And I recognize them as well.

05:43.908 --> 05:47.216
Oh, we were all at a bio-chem
conference together.

05:47.259 --> 05:51.176
We were panelists
on an Applied Sciences lecture.

05:51.220 --> 05:53.788
It's been looking for me
this whole time.

05:53.831 --> 05:55.964
- That still
doesn't explain why

05:56.007 --> 05:57.705
the fire's coming after you.

06:00.229 --> 06:02.492
- Because the fire is Ronnie,

06:02.536 --> 06:03.798
and he wants me to save him.

06:03.841 --> 06:06.627
[edgy music]

06:06.670 --> 06:09.325
♪

06:12.720 --> 06:14.417
- I know how this sounds,

06:14.461 --> 06:16.419
but it spoke to me.

06:16.463 --> 06:19.204
It was confused and jumbled,
but...

06:19.248 --> 06:21.642
it was him, it was Ronnie.

06:21.685 --> 06:23.426
- Caitlin, this fire,

06:23.470 --> 06:26.603
you know, it can get inside
people's heads,

06:26.647 --> 06:30.607
show you people you've lost,
like it did with Chester's dad.

06:30.651 --> 06:32.522
Are you sure
it didn't just want you

06:32.566 --> 06:34.002
to think it was Ronnie?

06:34.045 --> 06:36.483
- I wasn't sure at first.

06:36.526 --> 06:38.702
But that's why
I downloaded the data

06:38.746 --> 06:41.705
from when the fire
was in the NCCU.

06:41.749 --> 06:43.751
This is cold fusion radiation,

06:43.794 --> 06:46.318
but these readings are
10-to-the-negative 28 watts.

06:46.362 --> 06:49.104
- That's Hawking radiation.

06:49.147 --> 06:50.279
You can only pick up
rads like that

06:50.322 --> 06:52.542
from inside a Singularity.

06:52.586 --> 06:55.023
- Ronnie died
in a Singularity...

06:57.765 --> 06:59.723
- On our wedding day.

07:01.464 --> 07:02.987
The only way to close it

07:03.031 --> 07:04.902
was to merge the inner
and outer horizons.

07:04.946 --> 07:06.774
- Right.
Ronnie and Professor Stein

07:06.817 --> 07:09.124
came together, made Firestorm,

07:09.167 --> 07:11.126
then separated in that thing.

07:15.391 --> 07:16.827
- Ronnie!

07:16.871 --> 07:18.133
Professor!

07:19.526 --> 07:21.353
No!

07:24.618 --> 07:26.750
Only Ronnie didn't make it.
- Right.

07:26.794 --> 07:29.013
But matter cannot be
created or destroyed,

07:29.057 --> 07:30.145
only changed,

07:30.188 --> 07:32.626
so maybe Ronnie's still alive.

07:32.669 --> 07:35.933
I mean, maybe the pressure
from when the horizons merged

07:35.977 --> 07:37.457
broke down
his biological matter

07:37.500 --> 07:39.415
into pure thermodynamic energy.

07:39.459 --> 07:41.504
- That could account
for the radiation,

07:41.548 --> 07:42.853
but it still doesn't explain

07:42.897 --> 07:44.159
why the fire's
been killing people,

07:44.202 --> 07:45.769
why it tortured Chester.

07:45.813 --> 07:47.510
- And if Ronnie knew
what he was doing,

07:47.554 --> 07:49.033
he would hate it,

07:49.077 --> 07:52.036
which is why I don't think
he's in control.

07:52.080 --> 07:55.518
When Ronnie died, his brain
was flooded with ACTH.

07:55.562 --> 07:57.433
It's the hormone
the human brain creates

07:57.477 --> 07:59.087
when it experiences grief.

07:59.130 --> 08:02.394
So maybe when he was reborn
as a sentient fire,

08:02.438 --> 08:04.048
that same process gave him

08:04.092 --> 08:06.224
an overwhelming attraction
to the same hormone.

08:06.268 --> 08:09.184
- So he's been eating
people's grief

08:09.227 --> 08:11.926
because of some primal urge?

08:11.969 --> 08:13.797
- I think he needs it
to survive,

08:13.841 --> 08:15.407
which is why he's been trying
to reconnect with me

08:15.451 --> 08:16.496
so I can help him.

08:16.539 --> 08:18.106
- Did he say anything else?

08:18.149 --> 08:20.848
- A few words.
"Joining, togetherness."

08:20.891 --> 08:24.504
I think he was trying to get me
to remember something.

08:24.547 --> 08:26.375
- The Quantum splicer?

08:26.418 --> 08:29.944
- It's what made him Firestorm
in the first place.

08:29.987 --> 08:33.034
I think if we can use it
to make Ronnie human again,

08:33.077 --> 08:34.992
his mind will regain control.

08:35.036 --> 08:38.169
- And the killings will stop.

08:38.213 --> 08:41.216
- Even if you are right
about this,

08:41.259 --> 08:43.435
the splicer needs two people
to work,

08:43.479 --> 08:45.481
and we can't ask anybody
to volunteer.

08:45.525 --> 08:47.222
It's too dangerous.
- Yeah.

08:47.265 --> 08:49.093
But we wouldn't need
another person

08:49.137 --> 08:51.356
if we use one of
Eva McCulloch's R-CEM chips,

08:51.400 --> 08:54.621
'cause if we fuse one of Eva's
chips to the splicer,

08:54.664 --> 08:56.971
it'll do all the heavy lifting
by duplicating Ronnie cells

08:57.014 --> 08:58.842
and coalescing another body
for him, right?

08:58.886 --> 09:00.148
- Like it did
with Katie and me.

09:00.191 --> 09:02.542
- Okay, but raising the dead,

09:02.585 --> 09:04.544
that's intense, even for us.

09:04.587 --> 09:06.502
- Turned out okay
for Lazarus, right?

09:06.546 --> 09:08.939
- And if Chester and Caitlin
both think it might work...

09:08.983 --> 09:10.680
- It makes sense.

09:10.724 --> 09:13.596
Ronnie's just trying to help us
help him come home.

09:13.640 --> 09:15.119
All we have to do is listen.

09:15.163 --> 09:16.686
- What are we waiting for?

09:16.730 --> 09:18.470
- I'll get the Quantum splicer.

09:18.514 --> 09:20.821
- I'll grab an R-CEM chip
from the Starchives.

09:20.864 --> 09:24.999
♪

09:28.350 --> 09:30.308
- Hey.

09:30.352 --> 09:33.747
Things are moving pretty fast.

09:33.790 --> 09:34.878
- Not for Ronnie.
Who knows how long

09:34.922 --> 09:36.010
he's been trapped like that?

09:36.053 --> 09:37.272
- All I'm saying is let's not

09:37.315 --> 09:38.969
jump to conclusions

09:39.013 --> 09:40.580
about everything
that's been happening.

09:40.623 --> 09:43.408
You know,
maybe we just slow down

09:43.452 --> 09:45.802
and make sure
we're doing the right thing.

09:45.846 --> 09:48.326
- Saving my husband
is the right thing.

09:50.285 --> 09:53.201
Okay, if you want, we can
check the radiation data.

09:53.244 --> 09:55.899
- It's not the science
I'm worried about.

09:55.943 --> 09:57.335
This fire
can manipulate people.

09:57.379 --> 09:59.120
If it wants you
to use the splicer--

09:59.163 --> 10:02.427
- If I don't, Ronnie will be
burning like that forever,

10:02.471 --> 10:04.473
and I can't let that happen.

10:04.516 --> 10:06.693
Look, I know
what you're thinking.

10:06.736 --> 10:08.869
That I mourned his death
for so long

10:08.912 --> 10:11.828
that I would do anything
to get him back.

10:11.872 --> 10:14.483
But...Ronnie's alive.

10:14.526 --> 10:17.094
I--I can feel it, it's him.

10:17.138 --> 10:19.619
And he wants us to help him.

10:19.662 --> 10:21.185
I'm gonna take this to Chester

10:21.229 --> 10:23.274
so he can get started
on the modifications.

10:26.582 --> 10:27.888
- What is it?

10:27.931 --> 10:30.673
- Marcus.

10:30.717 --> 10:34.285
He has no idea what happened,
and...he deserves to know.

10:34.329 --> 10:36.113
- What are you gonna tell him?

10:37.637 --> 10:39.595
- The truth.

10:39.639 --> 10:41.641
- [sighs]

10:44.382 --> 10:46.733
- So you're saying
that for the last eight years,

10:46.776 --> 10:49.692
you've been
working with the Flash,

10:49.736 --> 10:52.521
and now your dead husband's
come back to life?

10:52.564 --> 10:54.392
- Yeah.

10:54.436 --> 10:55.916
- Yeah. Yeah, that's--

10:55.959 --> 10:58.614
that's kind of
out of my wheelhouse.

10:58.658 --> 11:00.703
- I know, and I just
want to make sure

11:00.747 --> 11:02.836
you're staying safe.

11:02.879 --> 11:08.363
Ronnie has been unconsciously
hurting the people around me.

11:08.406 --> 11:10.582
- And you think
I'm next on the list.

11:10.626 --> 11:14.195
- I'm so sorry
for dragging you into this,

11:14.238 --> 11:17.154
but...for your safety,

11:17.198 --> 11:20.723
I think we should stop
seeing each other

11:20.767 --> 11:23.857
just until I get Ronnie back.

11:23.900 --> 11:26.729
- And then what happens?
- Well, the killings will stop.

11:26.773 --> 11:29.210
- No, I meant
what happens with us?

11:30.341 --> 11:32.126
- Look, Marcus,
my last few relationships

11:32.169 --> 11:34.998
have not been exactly healthy.

11:35.042 --> 11:37.087
That's why I'd given up

11:37.131 --> 11:39.133
on finding a meaningful
connection with someone

11:39.176 --> 11:40.743
until I met you.

11:40.787 --> 11:45.313
And...you showed me that
when I go all in with us--

11:45.356 --> 11:47.054
- Look, Caitlin.

11:47.097 --> 11:49.839
Please, I'm not an idiot.

11:49.883 --> 11:51.449
There is no more us.

11:51.493 --> 11:53.582
And I've been broken up
with before.

11:53.625 --> 11:56.411
It's just never due
to resurrection.

11:56.454 --> 11:59.153
Yeah, that's a...
that's a new one.

12:01.808 --> 12:05.768
But it's your decision,
I guess,

12:05.812 --> 12:08.728
and I'll respect that.

12:08.771 --> 12:09.903
- I'm so sorry.

12:09.946 --> 12:12.383
- Yeah.

12:12.427 --> 12:15.386
Me too.

12:15.430 --> 12:19.739
Um, you know,
there's this quote from Plato

12:19.782 --> 12:22.785
that's always stuck with me.

12:22.829 --> 12:26.310
He said that plants grow
their roots towards the earth,

12:26.354 --> 12:29.096
but people,
we're heavenly plants,

12:29.139 --> 12:33.622
meaning that our roots,
they grow upward,

12:33.665 --> 12:36.364
towards our heart.

12:36.407 --> 12:38.975
But those roots,
they need to be cared for,

12:39.019 --> 12:42.500
tended, like any plant...

12:43.458 --> 12:45.199
Or your heart will break

12:45.242 --> 12:47.505
before it even
has a chance to grow.

12:50.857 --> 12:52.293
Goodbye, Caitlin.

12:52.336 --> 12:59.387
♪

13:05.088 --> 13:07.351
[tablet beeping]

13:10.050 --> 13:12.443
- What are you doing down here?

13:12.487 --> 13:15.838
- I'm making sure your RNA
is integrated into the sphere.

13:15.882 --> 13:17.709
Still the only way
to stop the flames.

13:17.753 --> 13:18.885
- Not anymore.

13:18.928 --> 13:20.234
We save Ronnie,

13:20.277 --> 13:21.496
and we can
chuck that time sphere

13:21.539 --> 13:24.151
in the trash.

13:24.194 --> 13:25.500
Come on, I thought
you were all about

13:25.543 --> 13:27.415
trusting your team now.
- I am.

13:27.458 --> 13:31.549
Caitlin's just so excited
about getting Ronnie back,

13:31.593 --> 13:35.640
it feels like she's ignoring
all the warning signs.

13:35.684 --> 13:37.512
I mean, Frost...

13:37.555 --> 13:39.731
if this was really Ronnie,

13:39.775 --> 13:43.692
why is he coming back now,
seven years after he died?

13:44.867 --> 13:46.738
- I don't know.

13:46.782 --> 13:47.870
- Neither do I.

13:49.741 --> 13:51.918
It just all feels...

13:51.961 --> 13:53.615
- Too good to be true?

13:55.660 --> 13:57.880
- Well,
you're checking on the sphere.

13:57.924 --> 13:59.490
You're worried about her too.

13:59.534 --> 14:01.579
- Maybe, but I can't start
fighting with her again.

14:01.623 --> 14:03.712
I mean, not after yesterday.

14:03.755 --> 14:06.323
She helped Mom and me.

14:06.367 --> 14:08.369
Gotta have her back now.

14:08.412 --> 14:10.762
- So what, we just let her
go through with this?

14:12.155 --> 14:13.591
- What if it was Iris,

14:13.635 --> 14:15.376
and there was some
dangerous experiment

14:15.419 --> 14:17.334
that would cure
her time sickness?

14:17.378 --> 14:20.163
You'd risk everything
to save her.

14:20.207 --> 14:22.383
So even if this fails,

14:22.426 --> 14:24.689
we at least owe her
the chance to try.

14:24.733 --> 14:28.389
♪

14:28.432 --> 14:30.870
- [beat boxing]

14:30.913 --> 14:32.959
♪ Yo it's me,
your boy Chester P. ♪

14:33.002 --> 14:34.482
♪ Ready to rock your world
with knowledge ♪

14:34.525 --> 14:38.094
♪ 100% for free,
free, free, free! ♪

14:38.138 --> 14:39.791
- You should sell merch,
you know?

14:39.835 --> 14:43.491
Like, shirts that say,
"What up, party people?"

14:43.534 --> 14:44.927
Like, all the way around.

14:44.971 --> 14:46.407
- All the way around, yeah?
- Yeah.

14:46.450 --> 14:48.191
- That's good,
I'm gonna steal that idea.

14:48.235 --> 14:50.150
- Wow, you really are
blowing up the internet.

14:50.193 --> 14:52.717
- Just wait
till my next episode, girl.

14:52.761 --> 14:54.154
Chhhh!

14:54.197 --> 14:57.244
- Hold on.
You're not sharing the specs

14:57.287 --> 14:58.941
for this online, are you?

14:58.985 --> 15:03.206
- Uh, yeah.
Live broadcasts, you know.

15:03.250 --> 15:08.124
- But then someone could
actually build it on their own.

15:08.168 --> 15:10.866
- Yeah, that's the point.

15:10.910 --> 15:13.303
Like, did you know that
WookieLover77

15:13.347 --> 15:15.305
built an entire fleet of drones

15:15.349 --> 15:16.959
based off of
my last AI algorithm?

15:17.003 --> 15:20.049
And now those same drones
are delivering supplies

15:20.093 --> 15:23.357
to folks who need them
in impoverished countries.

15:23.400 --> 15:25.228
That's what the whole
Chester P. community

15:25.272 --> 15:27.404
is all about.
[imitates airhorn]

15:27.448 --> 15:28.971
Shout out to WookieLover77,

15:29.015 --> 15:31.365
saving the world
one drone at a time.

15:31.408 --> 15:33.715
- And that's great.

15:35.282 --> 15:37.458
But the splicer isn't a drone,

15:37.501 --> 15:40.026
and putting technology
like this out there,

15:40.069 --> 15:41.592
it could be dangerous.

15:41.636 --> 15:43.333
What if it lands
in the wrong hands?

15:43.377 --> 15:46.380
- I'm pretty sure supervillains
have better things to do

15:46.423 --> 15:49.296
that watch my broadcast.

15:49.339 --> 15:51.951
Or worse things, I guess.

15:51.994 --> 15:54.431
- You still might
want to check yourself,

15:54.475 --> 15:56.477
depending on the science.

15:56.520 --> 15:58.653
- But that goes against
the whole purpose

15:58.696 --> 16:00.742
of scientific discovery.

16:00.785 --> 16:03.397
What good is knowledge
if you don't share it?

16:03.440 --> 16:06.748
Allegra, having access
to a breakthrough like this

16:06.791 --> 16:08.663
could help one of my viewers
better understand

16:08.706 --> 16:10.143
the laws of physics,
which could lead to

16:10.186 --> 16:12.928
who knows what kind
of innovation

16:12.972 --> 16:14.625
and make
the world a better place.

16:14.669 --> 16:17.802
Hell, someone could see this
and be inspired enough

16:17.846 --> 16:19.195
to land a breakthrough

16:19.239 --> 16:21.850
in the cosmology
of our bodies' atoms

16:21.893 --> 16:25.027
or maybe even
discover the true nature

16:25.071 --> 16:27.943
of what human consciousness
really is or...you know...

16:27.987 --> 16:30.293
- Or...

16:30.337 --> 16:31.991
how to resurrect the dead.

16:32.034 --> 16:34.994
[ominous music]

16:35.037 --> 16:39.346
♪

16:39.389 --> 16:41.304
Chuck, all I'm saying is

16:41.348 --> 16:47.180
maybe all knowledge shouldn't
always be so readily available.

16:47.223 --> 16:49.269
- 'Cause you think
most people are bad.

16:49.312 --> 16:50.748
- No.

16:50.792 --> 16:55.797
Because I know
most people aren't you.

16:55.840 --> 16:58.582
And maybe
they shouldn't be able

16:58.626 --> 17:02.673
to resurrect the past
on a whim.

17:02.717 --> 17:07.548
Last year, I watched
Esperanza die in my arms.

17:11.639 --> 17:15.730
Death shouldn't be some
kind of science experiment.

17:15.773 --> 17:19.908
It's a part of life
and it's finite.

17:19.951 --> 17:23.825
It's what my abuelita
used to call "noche mas negra,"

17:23.868 --> 17:26.175
the blackest night.

17:29.439 --> 17:31.180
- Yeah.

17:33.095 --> 17:35.880
I'll keep this one offline.

17:35.924 --> 17:38.622
- Well, hey,
think about that merch.

17:38.666 --> 17:41.190
[both laugh]

17:41.234 --> 17:43.149
I'll take a small.

17:43.192 --> 17:45.977
- I got you.
- Okay.

17:51.766 --> 17:53.594
[electricity buzzing]

17:53.637 --> 17:58.077
[eerie music]

17:58.120 --> 18:05.084
♪

18:05.127 --> 18:07.912
[electricity buzzing]

18:09.523 --> 18:13.788
[echoing whispers]
- Where is she? Where is she?

18:13.831 --> 18:16.617
- Ah, oh, God, no!

18:18.053 --> 18:21.491
- [guttural voice]
Where...is...she?

18:21.535 --> 18:24.451
♪

18:27.976 --> 18:30.500
- Where...is...Caitlin?

18:31.806 --> 18:34.896
Must be free!

18:34.939 --> 18:37.638
Pain...set free...

18:37.681 --> 18:39.118
- [whimpering]

18:39.161 --> 18:42.033
- Help...free me!

18:42.077 --> 18:45.167
- [whimpering]

18:45.211 --> 18:46.777
- Cecile.
- Oh!

18:46.821 --> 18:49.302
[panting]

18:49.345 --> 18:53.784
- What happened?
- [panting]

18:53.828 --> 18:55.569
[whispers]
The fire...

18:58.528 --> 18:59.921
It spoke to me.

18:59.964 --> 19:01.270
- It's here?

19:01.314 --> 19:02.967
- No.

19:04.665 --> 19:07.842
No, but...

19:07.885 --> 19:13.761
wherever it is,
it--it connected with my mind.

19:13.804 --> 19:17.286
Barry, the pain.

19:17.330 --> 19:19.288
The pain--
there was so much of it.

19:19.332 --> 19:21.725
- And Ronnie?

19:21.769 --> 19:23.858
Could you feel him too?

19:23.901 --> 19:28.515
- Yeah, I...could sense
his anguish.

19:30.473 --> 19:32.867
It felt like he was begging me.

19:32.910 --> 19:34.651
- To do what?

19:34.695 --> 19:37.567
- To set him free.

19:37.611 --> 19:38.916
Barry, I don't think that

19:38.960 --> 19:42.659
Ronnie wants to be
brought back.

19:42.703 --> 19:44.792
I think that he wants to die.

19:44.835 --> 19:48.665
[ominous music]

19:48.709 --> 19:50.276
- It's impossible.

19:50.319 --> 19:52.669
- Look, I know how hard
this must be to hear,

19:52.713 --> 19:57.283
but...I'm almost positive
about what I felt.

19:57.326 --> 20:00.460
Caitlin, Ronnie doesn't want
to be brought back.

20:00.503 --> 20:03.289
- He asked me to save him.

20:03.332 --> 20:05.987
- Maybe that's why
Ronnie went after Cecile.

20:06.030 --> 20:07.771
He knew he could
communicate through her

20:07.815 --> 20:08.859
to tell us the truth.

20:08.903 --> 20:10.992
- He's not here for Cecile.

20:11.035 --> 20:12.776
He's been looking for me.

20:12.820 --> 20:14.865
- From what I can tell...

20:16.519 --> 20:20.958
Ronnie is in agony
inside that fire.

20:21.002 --> 20:23.352
It's like it's eating
him alive.

20:23.396 --> 20:27.530
It's torturing his mind.

20:27.574 --> 20:30.794
Caitlin,
it's like Ronnie is in hell.

20:30.838 --> 20:35.364
And I truly believe that
he came to us for help.

20:36.931 --> 20:39.063
So that we can
end his suffering.

20:39.107 --> 20:40.717
- And we will.

20:40.761 --> 20:42.328
It's why we're modifying

20:42.371 --> 20:44.199
the Quantum splicer
to help him,

20:44.243 --> 20:46.984
because I know
that's what he would want.

20:47.028 --> 20:49.073
- What if Cecile's right?

20:49.117 --> 20:51.467
She's the only one
that's been able to form

20:51.511 --> 20:53.513
a true connection to the fire.

20:53.556 --> 20:56.429
- I'm connected to it
because I'm its wife.

20:56.472 --> 20:58.257
Why can't you understand that?

20:58.300 --> 21:00.781
I mean, if anyone knows
what it wants, it would be me!

21:00.824 --> 21:02.696
- You're right.

21:02.739 --> 21:06.700
You were... you are

21:06.743 --> 21:11.226
the most important thing
in Ronnie's life.

21:11.270 --> 21:15.752
Caitlin, maybe it's time
that you consider how he feels.

21:16.753 --> 21:20.148
- Barry, you knew Ronnie.
He was a part of this team,

21:20.191 --> 21:23.586
and you knew he'd do anything
to get back to me.

21:23.630 --> 21:26.067
We have a way to help him.

21:26.110 --> 21:28.112
Why are you so against this?

21:28.156 --> 21:31.377
- Because when I had
a chance like this once,

21:31.420 --> 21:34.554
when I went back
to save my mom from Thawne,

21:34.597 --> 21:38.645
I did it because I was trying
to recreate a perfect past.

21:38.688 --> 21:40.342
But it was a lie,

21:40.386 --> 21:42.301
and it all came crashing down
in the end

21:42.344 --> 21:44.433
because I refused
to see the warning signs,

21:44.477 --> 21:48.176
because I didn't listen
to my friends or my family.

21:48.219 --> 21:52.659
We can't...resurrect the past.

21:52.702 --> 21:54.051
It's too dangerous.

21:54.095 --> 21:56.140
- This is not
another Flashpoint.

21:56.184 --> 21:58.142
We are not creating
another timeline.

21:58.186 --> 22:00.841
We are saving my husband
from a nightmare.

22:00.884 --> 22:04.540
- Then maybe it's time
to help him let go.

22:06.455 --> 22:07.761
- I thought family was supposed
to have your back,

22:07.804 --> 22:09.806
no matter what.

22:09.850 --> 22:14.942
Even when they think
you're making the wrong choice.

22:14.985 --> 22:17.074
God knows, we've all fallen
in line for you and Iris

22:17.118 --> 22:18.467
on more than one occasion.

22:18.511 --> 22:21.078
- Caitlin, please.

22:21.122 --> 22:22.384
- If you won't help me,

22:22.428 --> 22:23.864
I'll save him on my own.

22:23.907 --> 22:26.867
[tense music]

22:26.910 --> 22:33.003
♪

22:36.703 --> 22:38.835
- Oh, yeah,
that's my kind of breakfast.

22:38.879 --> 22:40.446
- Good, you're awake.
- Barely.

22:40.489 --> 22:41.795
I haven't been up this early

22:41.838 --> 22:43.318
since Cisco
made me wait in line

22:43.362 --> 22:44.798
for the new "Call of Duty."
- [chuckles]

22:44.841 --> 22:46.495
Are we going somewhere?

22:46.539 --> 22:48.976
- I thought I'd surprise you
for our anniversary.

22:49.019 --> 22:52.196
- Okay, it's too early
for this. Spill it.

22:52.240 --> 22:54.634
- Okay, I thought we could use
a weekend away.

22:54.677 --> 22:57.854
Maybe get outside of the city,
go visit Mapleville.

22:57.898 --> 22:59.813
- Oh, okay,
I remember that place,

22:59.856 --> 23:01.989
where we had our
first weekend away together.

23:02.032 --> 23:04.818
- Which is why
I booked us a room

23:04.861 --> 23:06.472
at the same bed and breakfast
for a few nights.

23:06.515 --> 23:08.038
- Oh, yes.

23:08.082 --> 23:10.301
You remember that
seafood joint on the corner?

23:10.345 --> 23:12.391
We have to go back there.
- I do, and we will,

23:12.434 --> 23:14.349
just as soon as you get ready.

23:14.393 --> 23:15.437
Come on,
we gotta get on the road.

23:15.481 --> 23:17.004
It's a five-hour drive,

23:17.047 --> 23:18.745
and I want to be there
in time to check in,

23:18.788 --> 23:20.442
check out
the glassblowing exhibit.

23:20.486 --> 23:21.704
- Hold on, when exactly

23:21.748 --> 23:22.966
did you have time
to plan all this?

23:23.010 --> 23:24.228
- I know, we've been so busy

23:24.272 --> 23:25.360
with the particle accelerator,

23:25.404 --> 23:26.927
but I thought it was important

23:26.970 --> 23:28.407
to celebrate us.

23:28.450 --> 23:29.538
And the fact
that we've been together

23:29.582 --> 23:31.453
a whole year.
- A year.

23:31.497 --> 23:32.933
It has been
a pretty great year.

23:32.976 --> 23:35.283
- You think?
- I do.

23:35.326 --> 23:38.852
We're like two atoms
sharing a strong covalent bond.

23:38.895 --> 23:41.202
- I love it when you
talk science to me.

23:45.032 --> 23:46.860
Okay, now go. Go get ready.

23:46.903 --> 23:48.470
- Okay, I'm going,
I'm going, I'm going.

23:48.514 --> 23:51.255
I love you Cait.

24:00.787 --> 24:03.398
- [sighs]
Thank God you're okay.

24:03.442 --> 24:05.835
- [grunts]
Oh...

24:11.667 --> 24:13.060
Where's Tinya?

24:13.103 --> 24:14.975
- Well,
I told her to stay away.

24:15.018 --> 24:16.890
Your time sickness
is going ballistic.

24:16.933 --> 24:19.196
I figured it'd be better
to keep her safe.

24:19.240 --> 24:22.330
- Yeah, thank you.

24:22.373 --> 24:24.680
Look, Sue,
what happened to Tinya's mom,

24:24.724 --> 24:26.856
I didn't mean to--

24:26.900 --> 24:29.032
- I know, Iris.

24:29.076 --> 24:31.165
And I know that Deon
has told you to stay put

24:31.208 --> 24:33.167
until he can figure out
how to help you,

24:33.210 --> 24:36.083
but you are getting worse
by the hour.

24:36.126 --> 24:38.128
I really think that we should
get you to S.T.A.R. Labs--

24:38.172 --> 24:40.609
- No, don't!

24:40.653 --> 24:42.524
It might happen to you too.

24:42.568 --> 24:45.222
- Oh, so now you're worried
about hurting people?

24:45.266 --> 24:47.311
- Tinya, look,
I'm so sorry about

24:47.355 --> 24:48.965
what happened to your mom.

24:49.009 --> 24:51.707
[moans]
- Okay, I need to get her home,

24:51.751 --> 24:53.143
back to Central City.

24:53.187 --> 24:55.842
- Well, it's too late.
Now walk away.

24:55.885 --> 24:58.627
- Tinya.
- Shut up!

24:58.671 --> 25:02.892
- Tinya,
you don't want to do this.

25:02.936 --> 25:04.894
- Yeah, I do.

25:08.028 --> 25:09.682
- [screams]

25:13.033 --> 25:14.251
- What did you do to her?

25:14.295 --> 25:15.557
- Exactly what I'll do to you

25:15.601 --> 25:18.604
if you ever try to
find me again.

25:22.825 --> 25:24.087
- Wait, so Ronnie said

25:24.131 --> 25:25.828
he doesn't
want to be brought back?

25:25.872 --> 25:28.178
- He just wants to be released

25:28.222 --> 25:30.616
from whatever prison
he's been in all this time.

25:30.659 --> 25:32.705
- But if we don't save Ronnie,

25:32.748 --> 25:35.098
the fire
will keep killing people.

25:35.142 --> 25:37.361
- No, it won't.

25:37.405 --> 25:39.450
We're not gonna let the fire
kill anyone else.

25:39.494 --> 25:41.496
We're gonna stop it.

25:41.540 --> 25:43.193
The only way we can.

25:43.237 --> 25:45.935
- You're gonna use the Cold
Fusion Sphere to trap it.

25:45.979 --> 25:48.677
- And end Ronnie's pain,
once and for all.

25:48.721 --> 25:52.681
♪

25:56.380 --> 25:57.904
- I wish things were different,

25:57.947 --> 26:01.603
but we gotta do this,
for Ronnie's sake.

26:01.647 --> 26:04.998
- And we're sure
this is what Ronnie wants?

26:08.131 --> 26:09.916
- Yeah.

26:09.959 --> 26:12.658
- I mean, it would explain
why he's come back

26:12.701 --> 26:15.269
and why he was so desperate
to connect with Caitlin.

26:15.312 --> 26:20.361
- And helping Ronnie move on
would keep the city safe.

26:20.404 --> 26:23.625
- What about that
Quantum splicer thingy?

26:23.669 --> 26:25.627
Can't you at least try that?

26:25.671 --> 26:27.542
- [sighs]
The Quantum splicer works

26:27.586 --> 26:30.153
by bombarding the user's atoms
with energy to create fission,

26:30.197 --> 26:32.808
but it requires
the participant to be willing.

26:32.852 --> 26:34.505
If Ronnie rejects the splicer,

26:34.549 --> 26:38.292
his atomic structures
would become unstable,

26:38.335 --> 26:40.511
resulting in
an endothermic explosion.

26:40.555 --> 26:42.644
- He's not gonna try.

26:44.646 --> 26:47.257
All Ronnie wants now
is to be at peace.

26:48.911 --> 26:50.609
- Okay.

26:50.652 --> 26:52.262
If this is what we're doing,
then what's the plan?

26:52.306 --> 26:54.482
- We'd use the Cold Fusion
Sphere, just like before,

26:54.525 --> 26:56.615
only this time without
putting anyone in danger.

26:56.658 --> 26:58.181
And then once
it's trapped inside--

26:58.225 --> 27:01.663
- You just need to remove
the oxidizing agents,

27:01.707 --> 27:04.753
and it's bye-bye flames
for good.

27:04.797 --> 27:07.408
- I know how this sounds,

27:07.451 --> 27:11.847
but it feels like it's what
the Ronnie we knew wants.

27:11.891 --> 27:14.067
We have to honor that.

27:16.896 --> 27:18.680
Okay, um,
I'm gonna talk to Caitlin.

27:18.724 --> 27:21.291
She needs to know--
- No, I'll do it.

27:21.335 --> 27:23.380
She should hear it from me.

27:32.128 --> 27:35.262
[engine revving]

27:35.305 --> 27:38.700
- Go, go, go!
Come on, go, go, go!

27:38.744 --> 27:41.616
[engine straining]

27:42.530 --> 27:44.358
- No, no, no, Cait,
come on, we almost got it!

27:44.401 --> 27:46.534
- Ugh, you said that
20 minutes ago.

27:46.577 --> 27:48.318
It's fine, it doesn't matter.

27:48.362 --> 27:50.059
We missed our check in
for the bed and breakfast.

27:50.103 --> 27:51.713
We are stranded
in the middle of nowhere

27:51.757 --> 27:53.715
with no cell service.
- Okay, okay.

27:53.759 --> 27:56.152
- So much
for a romantic weekend away.

27:56.196 --> 27:57.980
I had big plans, you know?

27:58.024 --> 28:00.417
Plans that did not involve
us getting pneumonia.

28:00.461 --> 28:02.202
- Well, I had big plans too,
all right?

28:02.245 --> 28:04.291
- Yeah, well not like my plans.

28:04.334 --> 28:06.380
Mine were once-in-a-generation,
tell your grandkids,

28:06.423 --> 28:07.947
get down on one knee
kind of plans.

28:07.990 --> 28:11.298
- Whoa, whoa, whoa,
you were gonna propose?

28:13.343 --> 28:14.736
- Yes.

28:14.780 --> 28:17.086
Because I love you
so much, Ronnie Raymond,

28:17.130 --> 28:19.785
it freaks me out.

28:19.828 --> 28:21.743
But everything is ruined now.

28:21.787 --> 28:25.312
- No, no, no, no,
it's not ruined, okay?

28:25.355 --> 28:26.835
I know you wanted to go
to that bed and breakfast

28:26.879 --> 28:29.751
where we first fell in love,
but maybe

28:29.795 --> 28:31.884
we need to stop trying
to recreate the past

28:31.927 --> 28:34.408
and focus on the future, okay?

28:34.451 --> 28:38.281
Because when I look at you,
I see forever,

28:38.325 --> 28:39.979
and I want forever
to start right now.

28:40.022 --> 28:42.459
- Me too.

28:42.503 --> 28:44.984
In that case...
- Hold on.

28:45.027 --> 28:46.463
Wait.
- Ronnie Raymond--

28:46.507 --> 28:48.378
- Wait, wait, wait.

28:51.077 --> 28:52.469
- [chuckles]

28:54.471 --> 28:56.691
- I told you I had big plans.

28:56.735 --> 28:58.519
- Great minds...

28:58.562 --> 29:01.087
- My answer's yes, by the way.
- So is mine.

29:01.130 --> 29:05.265
♪

29:07.528 --> 29:09.530
- [sighs]

29:10.574 --> 29:13.839
We need to talk.

29:13.882 --> 29:15.710
Barry wants to use
the Fusion sphere

29:15.754 --> 29:17.799
to help Ronnie die,
and the team's on board.

29:17.843 --> 29:20.497
- I'm not surprised
after everything he said.

29:20.541 --> 29:23.065
I just never thought
you'd go along with it.

29:25.111 --> 29:27.069
- I'm really worried, Catie.

29:27.113 --> 29:28.810
- Then why won't you help me?

29:28.854 --> 29:31.682
- Not about Ronnie, about you.

29:31.726 --> 29:34.033
Look, when Ronnie died,

29:34.076 --> 29:35.817
you and me
weren't even you and me.

29:35.861 --> 29:37.950
I was still
in your subconscious.

29:37.993 --> 29:41.214
But even then,
I could feel your pain

29:41.257 --> 29:43.694
the moment
you realized he was gone.

29:43.738 --> 29:45.653
And that night
when you went to bed,

29:45.696 --> 29:47.829
and every night after that.

29:47.873 --> 29:49.613
But as bad as that was,

29:49.657 --> 29:51.180
watching you pull away

29:51.224 --> 29:55.228
from everyone who loves you
was even worse,

29:55.271 --> 29:57.056
and it's happening again.

29:57.099 --> 30:00.886
- I'm sorry
you felt all that pain.

30:00.929 --> 30:04.498
But did you feel anything else?

30:04.541 --> 30:06.805
- I remember how happy
you were before he died.

30:09.459 --> 30:11.897
Which is why I got this.

30:11.940 --> 30:13.768
- What about Barry?

30:13.812 --> 30:17.250
- Sure, Barry's family,
but you're blood,

30:17.293 --> 30:18.991
and I will always
have your back.

30:19.034 --> 30:20.731
- [sighs]

30:23.604 --> 30:25.388
- But you got to promise
me something, all right?

30:25.432 --> 30:29.871
You will never shut
yourself off from me

30:29.915 --> 30:31.264
or the rest of the team,
all right?

30:31.307 --> 30:33.788
- I promise.
And, Frost...

30:35.137 --> 30:37.444
Thank you.
- You got it.

30:37.487 --> 30:39.315
Let's go find Ronnie.

30:39.359 --> 30:42.188
- Okay, great.
How do we do that?

30:42.231 --> 30:44.668
- We'll search this
whole damn city to find him,

30:44.712 --> 30:47.323
day or night,
rain or snow, or whatever.

30:47.367 --> 30:49.238
We're gonna find him.

30:49.282 --> 30:51.632
- That's it. Rain or snow.

30:51.675 --> 30:53.329
"Memories in the snow."

30:53.373 --> 30:55.114
That's what he was
trying to tell me.

30:55.157 --> 30:57.072
- What are you talking about?

30:57.116 --> 30:58.639
- I know where to find Ronnie.

31:03.949 --> 31:10.172
- The kids swore they heard
a voice calling them.

31:10.216 --> 31:13.872
They looked under their bed
and they saw nothing.

31:15.177 --> 31:20.661
And they looked out
the window and saw nothing.

31:21.705 --> 31:26.449
So they went to sleep,
thinking they were safe.

31:26.493 --> 31:32.238
But the children,
they never looked...

31:32.281 --> 31:33.282
up!

31:33.326 --> 31:36.372
[laughter]

31:37.504 --> 31:41.682
[growl rumbling]

31:41.725 --> 31:44.685
[eerie music]

31:44.728 --> 31:46.078
♪

31:46.121 --> 31:48.036
- Is someone there?

31:48.080 --> 31:51.126
- [scoffs]
It's probably just the wind.

31:54.477 --> 31:57.132
[fire roaring]

32:00.048 --> 32:03.095
[intense music]

32:03.138 --> 32:09.579
♪

32:13.322 --> 32:14.584
- Barometric scans
just picked up an anomaly

32:14.628 --> 32:15.934
at Piedmont State Park.

32:15.977 --> 32:17.370
- And a half a dozen
heat signatures.

32:17.413 --> 32:18.719
- We need to move.
Chester?

32:18.762 --> 32:20.373
- Okay, the sphere is ready.

32:20.416 --> 32:22.331
Once the fire's trapped,
this deoxygenator node

32:22.375 --> 32:23.942
will activate and the flames
will be snuffed out.

32:23.985 --> 32:25.160
- Okay.

32:25.204 --> 32:26.770
- Where's Frost?
- I don't know.

32:26.814 --> 32:29.512
We gotta go.
Hang on.

32:29.556 --> 32:32.211
[intense music]

32:32.254 --> 32:35.997
♪

32:36.041 --> 32:38.043
- Everyone head
for the park entrance.

32:38.086 --> 32:39.914
Keep going towards
the brightest lights you see.

32:39.958 --> 32:42.003
The rest of my team
will get you to safety.

32:43.309 --> 32:45.659
Allegra, Cecile, six civilians
are heading your way.

32:45.702 --> 32:47.139
- We'll keep an eye out.

32:47.182 --> 32:48.836
- And I'll keep
lighting the way.

32:48.879 --> 32:53.580
- Hunger, feed...

32:53.623 --> 32:56.017
- I'm sorry, Ronnie.

32:56.061 --> 32:59.412
- No!

33:04.765 --> 33:06.506
- The sphere's heating up.

33:06.549 --> 33:09.074
I'm not sure how much longer
I can hold this.

33:09.117 --> 33:10.597
- You're almost there.

33:10.640 --> 33:16.037
Okay, barometric readings
are 60%, 50%, 40%.

33:16.081 --> 33:18.561
Frack, looks like there's
more civilians incoming

33:18.605 --> 33:22.043
and they're moving
really, really fast.

33:22.087 --> 33:25.220
[fire growling]

33:29.572 --> 33:34.403
♪

33:39.582 --> 33:41.280
- What did you do?

33:41.323 --> 33:43.934
- Exactly what we had to.

33:43.978 --> 33:47.851
[fire roaring]

33:54.249 --> 33:56.773
- You just destroyed our best
shot at stopping this thing.

33:56.817 --> 33:59.254
- It's not a thing.
It's my husband.

33:59.298 --> 34:01.387
- You're gonna
get yourself killed.

34:01.430 --> 34:03.476
- It's her decision, let her.

34:06.131 --> 34:09.090
[gentle music]

34:09.134 --> 34:16.358
♪

34:16.402 --> 34:18.143
- Caitlin, whatever happens...

34:19.144 --> 34:21.581
- Ronnie!

34:24.540 --> 34:27.326
- We promised each other we'd
spend our futures together.

34:30.633 --> 34:33.593
I'm keeping that promise.

34:33.636 --> 34:40.687
♪

34:52.220 --> 34:55.180
[epic music]

34:55.223 --> 35:01.969
♪

35:10.456 --> 35:12.153
- It's you.

35:12.197 --> 35:14.634
It's really you.

35:14.677 --> 35:16.853
- Cait, you did it.

35:16.897 --> 35:18.420
You saved me.

35:23.208 --> 35:24.209
[groans]

35:26.559 --> 35:30.302
- You're okay, you're okay.

35:30.345 --> 35:32.391
We're both okay now.

35:32.434 --> 35:38.136
♪

35:49.190 --> 35:52.759
[uneasy music]

35:52.802 --> 35:56.806
♪

35:56.850 --> 35:59.679
- Ronnie's still recovering
from the massive energy surge

35:59.722 --> 36:01.289
to his system,
but he's stable.

36:01.333 --> 36:02.856
- Oh, thank God.

36:02.899 --> 36:04.858
- There's still an occasional
irregularity

36:04.901 --> 36:07.121
in his amygdala function that
I haven't quite figured out,

36:07.165 --> 36:09.558
but it should improve
when he gets his strength back.

36:09.602 --> 36:11.169
- He's been through a lot.

36:11.212 --> 36:12.648
I guess it would be weird
if he didn't have

36:12.692 --> 36:14.389
some kind of reaction.

36:14.433 --> 36:17.827
- We're all just glad
that he's back, Caitlin.

36:17.871 --> 36:20.743
- Joe's right. We're all
so happy for you, honey.

36:20.787 --> 36:22.397
- Thank you.

36:22.441 --> 36:24.486
- I've got
more good news, y'all.

36:24.530 --> 36:27.663
So I've had satellites running
barometric scans all night.

36:27.707 --> 36:32.015
There's been zero sign
of our angry inferno anywhere,

36:32.059 --> 36:34.714
not one flicker.

36:34.757 --> 36:36.890
- Caity was right.
Now that Ronnie's human again,

36:36.933 --> 36:39.066
no more grief eating monster.

36:39.109 --> 36:42.722
- Caitlin,
I'm sorry I ever doubted you.

36:42.765 --> 36:45.464
I was wrong the whole time.
- It's okay.

36:45.507 --> 36:46.987
You were just trying to do
what you thought was right.

36:47.030 --> 36:49.598
- We all lose faith sometimes,

36:49.642 --> 36:51.470
but the point is,

36:51.513 --> 36:55.343
we brought one of our
family members back here.

36:55.387 --> 36:56.866
- Yeah, that sounds
great to me,

36:56.910 --> 36:59.129
and I can't wait
to get to know him.

36:59.173 --> 37:00.783
- I actually think
the two of you

37:00.827 --> 37:02.742
are really gonna get along.

37:02.785 --> 37:04.309
And you too, Chester.

37:04.352 --> 37:06.180
- What makes you say that?

37:06.224 --> 37:09.270
- I mean, I probably
shouldn't be saying this

37:09.314 --> 37:12.099
because it was a long time ago,

37:12.142 --> 37:16.451
but he mentioned that
maybe once he, you know...

37:16.495 --> 37:18.453
- No, seriously?

37:18.497 --> 37:20.063
- What?

37:20.107 --> 37:21.543
What?

37:21.587 --> 37:23.806
- Ronnie played D&D in college?

37:23.850 --> 37:26.374
- Once or twice.
- Oh, snap!

37:26.418 --> 37:28.768
We're gonna help him
get his game on, girl.

37:28.811 --> 37:31.510
Once he's better
and all that, of course.

37:31.553 --> 37:33.642
- Whatever happened
to chess or checkers?

37:33.686 --> 37:34.991
- Dominoes.

37:35.035 --> 37:36.036
- That's a good game
right there.

37:36.079 --> 37:38.647
- Okay, Grandpa.
- [gasps]

37:38.691 --> 37:41.041
- Uh, Caitlin...

37:42.477 --> 37:45.393
For what it's worth,
I'm so sorry.

37:45.437 --> 37:46.742
I don't know.
My powers, they've just--

37:46.786 --> 37:50.833
they've never been
so off before.

37:50.877 --> 37:52.792
I just wish I knew
why I got it so wrong.

37:52.835 --> 37:54.272
- That's okay.

37:54.315 --> 37:55.925
All that matters
is that Ronnie's home.

37:55.969 --> 37:58.232
- Yeah.

38:02.802 --> 38:06.371
[line rings]

38:06.414 --> 38:09.809
- Hi, I'm not here right now,
leave a message.

38:09.852 --> 38:11.593
- Voicemail again.

38:11.637 --> 38:14.292
[knocking at door]

38:14.335 --> 38:16.729
- Barry?
It's Sue.

38:18.426 --> 38:21.386
[soft dramatic music]

38:21.429 --> 38:23.518
♪

38:23.562 --> 38:27.261
- Hi, uh,
they told me you were here.

38:29.698 --> 38:32.048
- Where's Iris?

38:32.092 --> 38:34.660
- I don't know.

38:34.703 --> 38:36.488
I just know that she's missing.

38:36.531 --> 38:39.447
[dark music]

38:39.491 --> 38:41.928
[heartbeat thumping loudly]
Her mom just vanished,

38:41.971 --> 38:44.017
and then Iris too.

38:44.060 --> 38:46.367
Barry, I am so sorry.

38:46.411 --> 38:48.195
Barry. Barry!

38:48.238 --> 38:49.892
Did you hear what I said?

38:49.936 --> 38:51.372
Iris is gone.

38:51.416 --> 38:53.940
♪

38:57.813 --> 38:59.119
- Another spike.

38:59.162 --> 39:02.165
Ronnie, we need to check your--

39:02.209 --> 39:04.429
Ronnie?

39:04.472 --> 39:07.432
[eerie music]

39:07.475 --> 39:14.526
♪

39:50.126 --> 39:53.303
- Caitlin.

39:53.347 --> 39:57.830
Caitlin.

39:57.873 --> 39:59.832
- Ronnie?

39:59.875 --> 40:03.401
- Caitlin.

40:05.881 --> 40:08.754
- Ronnie?

40:08.797 --> 40:11.409
Ronnie,

40:11.452 --> 40:14.499
did you hear that voice?

40:14.542 --> 40:17.327
- I did.

40:17.371 --> 40:19.547
'Cause that voice was mine.

40:19.591 --> 40:21.941
♪

40:21.984 --> 40:23.551
I called you here
to show you that I feel

40:23.595 --> 40:26.249
stronger than ever now,

40:26.293 --> 40:27.555
thanks to this.

40:27.599 --> 40:30.297
♪

40:30.340 --> 40:32.647
I knew you'd understand
what I wanted, Cait,

40:32.691 --> 40:36.608
and that you'd build
exactly what I needed.

40:36.651 --> 40:38.914
♪

40:38.958 --> 40:41.395
- Something's wrong.

40:41.439 --> 40:44.485
We need to get you
back to the med lab.

40:44.529 --> 40:46.356
- No.

40:46.400 --> 40:48.402
I'm not going anywhere.

40:48.446 --> 40:50.491
Not yet.

40:50.535 --> 40:52.232
- Ronnie, you're scaring me.

40:52.275 --> 40:58.978
- That's probably because
I'm not Ronnie.

41:00.196 --> 41:01.763
- Where's my husband?

41:01.807 --> 41:03.722
- He's dead.

41:03.765 --> 41:05.288
Your friends were right.

41:05.332 --> 41:07.813
Ronnie Raymond sacrificed
himself to the storm

41:07.856 --> 41:09.336
in the Singularity,

41:09.379 --> 41:11.773
gave his life to its power,

41:11.817 --> 41:14.472
his future
to ensure its demise.

41:14.515 --> 41:16.561
But in that

41:16.604 --> 41:20.478
uncontrollable,
irreversible chaos,

41:20.521 --> 41:23.698
his death gave me life.

41:23.742 --> 41:26.309
Now I'm something greater,

41:26.353 --> 41:29.965
something beyond death.

41:31.619 --> 41:34.579
[intense music]

41:34.622 --> 41:41.673
♪

41:43.152 --> 41:46.634
I am Death Storm.

41:46.678 --> 41:50.246
♪

41:53.772 --> 41:56.731
[epic music]

41:56.775 --> 42:03.825
♪

42:12.878 --> 42:14.314
- Greg, move your head.
